+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Stage 2: Enable Structured Logging --- Repeat the Attack**          |
|                                                                       |
| *The same attack --- different outcome for the defender*              |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

  --------------------------------- -------------------------------------
  **What to Do**                    **What You Should Observe**

  --------------------------------- -------------------------------------

+--------------------------------+-------------------------------------+
| **2a. Stop the vulnerable app  | **You should now see structured     |
| (Ctrl+C)**                     | JSON security events:**             |
|                                |                                     |
| **2b. Start the fixed app with | {\"ti                               |
| structured logging**           | mestamp\":\"2026-03-17T09:43:12Z\", |
|                                |                                     |
| python3                        | \"event\":\"LOGIN_FAILURE\",        |
| vulnerable_shop_fixed.py       |                                     |
|                                | \"username\":\"admin\",             |
| *(Port 5001 --- the Module 11  |                                     |
| Flask Supplement logging code  | \"source_ip\":\"127.0.0.1\",        |
| is already integrated in this  |                                     |
| version)*                      | \"success\":false,                  |
|                                |                                     |
| **2c. Repeat the SQLi attempt  | \"detail\":\"invalid_credentials\"} |
| --- same payload**             |                                     |
|                                | **Now answer the same questions:**  |
| Username: admin\' \--          |                                     |
|                                | -   **Who was targeted?** →         |
| Password: anything             |     \"admin\"                       |
|                                |                                     |
| → Click Login (expect:         | -   **What payload was used?** →    |
| Forbidden)                     |     Visible in event detail         |
|                                |                                     |
| **2d. Repeat 10 times --- then | -   **Did auth succeed?** →         |
| try a valid login**            |     \"success\": false              |
|                                |                                     |
| Username: alice Password:      | -   **How many attempts?** → Count  |
| password123                    |     LOGIN_FAILURE events            |
|                                |                                     |
| Watch the terminal output      | -   **Source?** → \"source_ip\" on  |
| carefully.                     |     every event                     |
|                                |                                     |
|                                | **The attack is now detectable,     |
|                                | attributable, and countable.**      |
|                                |                                     |
|                                | A SIEM rule alerting on 5+          |
|                                | LOGIN_FAILURE events in 60 seconds  |
|                                | from the same IP would have         |
|                                | triggered an alert after the third  |
|                                | attempt.                            |
